    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1921-09-06T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1921-09-06T00:00:00-05:00" n="504"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d504">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">817.24/9</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Secretary of War</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Weeks</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1921-09-06">
                            <hi rend="italic">September 6, 1921</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">ASW 400.703</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">My Dear Mr. Secretary</hi>: I have the honor to acknowledge
                    receipt of your letter of August 27, 1921, with its enclosure from the
                    Nicaraguan Minister regarding the purchase of— <list>
                        <item>5,000 rifles;</item>
                        <item>3,000,000 cartridges for same;</item>
                        <item>25 machine guns;</item>
                        <item>250,000 rounds of ammunition for machine guns</item>
                        <item>2 military aeroplanes, with their regulation supply of ammunition and
                            indispensable spare parts.</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <p>The War Department at the present time is in a position to negotiate a sale of
                    all of the above mentioned equipment to the Nicaraguan Government except the
                    5,000 rifles. The availability of the rifles for sale will be determined at a
                    later date, but, undoubtedly, before the negotiations for the purchase of the
                    other material are concluded.</p>
                <p>It is understood, of course, that this sale is sanctioned by the State
                    Department.</p>
                <p>Sincerely yours,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">John W. Weeks</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
